english:
  title: A Memorial of Earnest Petition
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: "Your humble servant bows respectfully and prostrates twice before the Purple Palace of His Majesty the Emperor.\n\nYour servant has already submitted a memorial expressing a matter or two of grave concern, yet there remain grievances that weigh heavily upon the heart, unable to find full voice. These matters could not be comprehensively recorded within that previous memorial, and so your servant submits this document to lay bare what remains unspoken. The account is tangled and complex, and your servant fears it may exhaust the imperial patience. Yet I humbly beseech Your Majesty's clemency to grant this humble work your consideration.\n\nOur small nation has always been a realm beyond the seas. Through the generations, we have survived only by practicing the rites of serving the greater power. Thus did we once serve the Great Jin, and when that kingdom fell into ruin, we ceased our tributary practices. In the year of the Rat, when the Khitans raised a great army and crossed into our borders, ravaging our lands with violence, our great benefactor sent the general Ha Ching-cha-la with troops to rescue us. In a single sweep, the invaders were vanquished. Our small nation, overwhelmed by such boundless grace, performed the rites of submission and made a sacred covenant beneath heaven, pledging ten thousand years of peace. When we inquired about the proper manner and timing of our annual tributes, the general replied: \"The roads are treacherous, and your realm will surely find travel difficult. Each year we shall send no more than ten envoys. Let them carry back your tributes on their return. When our emissaries journey to your land, they shall pass through the territory of Manno—take this as your sign.\"\n\nFor some time thereafter, the exchanges proceeded according to this arrangement. Each year our nation would entrust our national credentials and precious gifts to the Yuan envoys for presentation at the imperial court. Yet in the year of the Monkey, the envoy Cheok-ko-yeo arrived not by way of Manno's territory, but by the alternate road of Pa-sok. We received him with the same respect as before and dispatched our national credentials as was customary. \n\nBut gradually the visits of envoys grew sparse. Our small nation began to wonder at this change. Much later we learned the bitter truth: U-ga-ha had waylaid and murdered our envoys upon the road. After committing this treachery, U-ga-ha donned the imperial insignia and invaded our northern borders, destroying three cities. Manno likewise attacked our eastern territories and took two cities, both wearing the colors and dress of the great power. The incursions continued without cease.\n\nMoreover, when envoys of the Yuan journeyed toward our land, Manno would intercept them, spreading false word: \"Goryeo has betrayed you—proceed no further.\" But our envoys, refusing to be deterred and desiring to know truth from deception, continued on their way. Manno then sent his men ahead, dressed in our national garb and bearing our weapons. They lay in ambush in the mountain valleys between our lands, waiting for our envoys to pass. When they emerged and fired upon them, they left word with the survivors: \"See what Goryeo has done—their treachery is clear. You must turn back.\" But by fortune, one man named Wang-ho-bi escaped from Manno's forces and came to us with the full account of this deception, so our nation learned the truth.\n\nNot long after, we heard that a great army had crossed into our realm. Because we maintained peaceful relations, we could scarcely believe the Yuan forces had come. We did not understand the cause of their invasion until the great commander Sa-ri-ta sent word demanding: \"Why did your nation kill our envoy Cheok-ko-yeo and shoot our envoys on the eastern road?\"\n\nSince we had already learned the true facts, we provided a full and honest account. We performed the rites of submission once more, and the great army, having thoroughly investigated the treacherous deeds of those two villains, suddenly understood the truth. They withdrew their forces and granted us mercy.\n\nAs the great army departed, we hastened to send envoys bearing our national credentials and tributes to lay before the imperial throne. Our ruler and ministers rejoiced together, saying: \"For so long the roads were closed, and we could not fulfill our tributary duties. We strayed far from our original covenant of friendship, and this weighed upon us constantly. Now that we have sent envoys to demonstrate our sincerity, surely this is cause for celebration. Moreover, the great power had always blamed U-ga-ha and Manno's crimes upon us, leaving us with no means to vindicate ourselves. We feared to let others speak lest false accusations fall upon us. But by the grace of the great army's personal investigation, the imperial suspicions have melted away like ice in spring. We are freed from the weight of these accusations and can now settle our hearts and direct all our efforts to serving the supreme power.\"\n\nYet within a brief time, a man named Song-lip-chang, who was traveling with an envoy, fled from the Yuan court with alarming news: \"The great power has already resolved to raise an army and invade us.\" The people heard this and fell into panic. Many fled. We heard reports that rebels in one or two northern cities had persuaded the local commanders to slaughter innocent civilians and to murder the imperial official I had sent to receive the Yuan envoys. This man lay in ruin, his purpose unfulfilled. The rebels spread word that the great army was coming. We heard that Yuan envoys had arrived at Uiju and were preparing a thousand great ships to transport the imperial armies across our waters. Thus all our people, from highest to lowest, trembled in fear. More than half fled their homes. Empty houses stood everywhere, becoming overgrown with weeds. To witness this desolation filled the heart with unbearable sorrow.\n\nIn our distress, ruler and ministers consulted together: \"If all our remaining people scatter, the foundation of our nation will be empty. An empty foundation cannot produce tributes to serve the great power year after year. Would it not be better to gather our scattered people and dwell among the mountains and by the seas? Though our offerings might be humble, we could still maintain the name of a tributary state and not lose our dignity.\" We reasoned that the loyalty of the heart is not dependent upon geography. If we serve with genuine sincerity, surely the great power would not fault us for this. Thus we settled upon this course.\n\nSo our nation's migration was undertaken for no other purpose than this. We harbor no other intentions. Heaven and earth and the spirits witness the truth of our hearts.\n\nYet unexpectedly, the great power, moved by baseless rumors, sent forth a great army to our lands. Wherever they passed, they showed no mercy—neither to the old nor the young, neither to men nor to women. All were put to the sword. Our entire nation has lost its spirit and vigor. Our people live in terror and despair, with scarce a will to continue living.\n\nThe ruler is like heaven itself, like a parent. When a ruler and people face such great calamity and profound sorrow, to whom can they appeal if not to heaven and to their parent? \n\nYour humble servant humbly beseech Your Majesty the Emperor: With the compassion that heaven and earth and a parent show toward their children, please recognize that our small nation harbors no other intentions. I implore you to command the great army to return, to lower their banners, and to protect our small nation forever. Then your servant will redouble his efforts and sincerity, sending forth our humble products year after year, that we might demonstrate our undivided loyalty and offer endless blessings upon the Emperor's ten thousand and ten thousand years of reign. This is the prayer of your servant's heart.\n\nYour humble servant begs for Your Majesty's compassion. Looking upward to heaven, I can only express my deepest gratitude for your virtue and benevolence. With utmost reverence, your servant submits this memorial.\n\nHumbly submitted."
  footnotes:
    - This is a formal petition (狀, jang) submitted to the Yuan court, likely during the Goryeo period when Korea was under Yuan influence.
    - The 'year of the Rat' (丙子年) refers to 1216 when the Khitans invaded; the 'year of the Rabbit' (己卯年) refers to 1219 when Yuan forces came to aid Goryeo.
    - U-ga-ha and Manno (萬奴) were regional commanders or warlords whose treacherous actions precipitated the military crisis described in the petition.
    - The 'alternate road of Pa-sok' (婆速路) likely refers to a route that bypassed the agreed-upon Manno territory, which aroused suspicion about the envoy's authenticity.
    - This petition exemplifies the political precarity faced by Goryeo as a tributary state caught between competing powers, and Lee Gyubo's skill in classical rhetoric and diplomatic language.
